            End of Twitter post  by @Jeremy_Hunt
        
    

Mr Hedges' family previously said that during the first six weeks of his detention he had been interrogated without a lawyer and consular access was unavailable.Despite not speaking Arabic, he was made to sign a document which transpired to be a confession, they added.Ms Tejada said her husband had been left "absolutely terrified" by the prospect of serving a life sentence in the UAE and was suffering panic attacks.Mr Hedges, who lives in Exeter, was arrested at Dubai Airport in May.
                
                
                
                
                
